@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(xiv) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it uses an ATOM literal (`:red`). eval represents it as a VAtom that
-- displays `:red`; `lowerLit` in the compiler refuses an atom literal — it would need a
-- tagged runtime value (a `$atom("red")` wrapper whose `$show` reproduces value.ts's `:name`
-- display, the same `$t`-tag scheme tuples/ctors/records/lists use). The differential
-- harness must report it `unsupported` — a CLEAN refusal at the compiler frontier.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values;
-- D1(viii) PAST first-class `def` references; D1(ix) PAST first-class BUILTIN references;
-- D1(x) PAST short-circuit `&&`/`||`; D1(xi) PAST non-tail `if` as a value; D1(xii) PAST
-- non-tail `match` as a value; D1(xiii) PAST multi-clause `def`s; D1(xiv) PAST reassignment
-- of a `mut` binding (see compile_reassign_test). The frontier now sits at ATOM literals.
-- This file uses one, so it still refuses; when atom literals lower (a later D1 slice, a
-- `$atom`-tagged value), it flips from `unsupported` to a print with no edit.

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  let c = :red
  println(c)
